Event Threading within News Topics 
content:
1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:With the overwhelming volume of online news available today, there is an increasing need for automatic techniques to analyze and present news to the user in a meaningful and efficient manner .
1-2:Previous research focused only on organizing news stories by their topics into a flat hierarchy .
1-3:We believe viewing a news topic as a flat collection of stories is too restrictive and inefficient for a user to understand the topic quickly .
1-4:In this work, we attempt to capture the rich structure of events and their dependencies in a news topic through our event models .
1-5:We call the process of recognizing events and their dependencies event threading .
1-6:We believe our perspective of modeling the structure of a topic is more effective in capturing its semantics than a flat list of on topic stories .
1-7:We formally define the novel problem, suggest evaluation metrics and present a few techniques for solving the problem .
1-8:Besides the standard word based features, our approaches take into account novel features such as temporal locality of stories for event recognition and time ordering for capturing dependencies .
1-9:Our experiments on a manually labeled data sets show that our models effectively identify the events and capture dependencies among them .
1-10:H.3.3 [Information Search and Retrieval]: Clustering .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:News forms a major portion of information disseminated in the world everyday .
2-2:Common people and news analysts alike are very interested in keeping abreast of new things that happen in the news, but it is becoming very difficult to cope with the huge volumes of information that arrives each day .
2-3:Hence there is an increasing need for automatic techniques to organize news stories in a way that helps users interpret and analyze them quickly .
2-4:This problem is addressed by a research program called Topic Detection and Tracking [3] that runs an open annual competition on standardized tasks of news organization .
2-5:One of the shortcomings of current TDT evaluation is its view of news topics as flat collection of stories .
2-6:For example, the detection task of TDT is to arrange a collection of news stories into clusters of topics .
2-7:However, a topic in news is more than a mere collection of stories: it is characterized by a definite structure of inter related events .
2-8:This is indeed recognized by TDT which defines a topic as ‘a set of news stories that are strongly related by some seminal realworld event" where an event is defined as ‘something that happens at a specific time and location" [3] .
2-9:For example, when a bomb explodes in a building, that is the seminal event that triggers the topic .
2-10:Other events in the topic may include the rescue attempts, the search for perpetrators, arrests and trials and so on .
2-11:We see that there is a pattern of dependencies between pairs of events in the topic .
2-12:In the above example, the event of rescue attempts is ‘influenced" by the event of bombing and so is the event of search for perpetrators .
2-13:In this work we investigate methods for modeling the structure of a topic in terms of its events .
2-14:By structure, we mean not only identifying the events that make up a topic, but also establishing dependencies generally causal among them .
2-15:We call the process of recognizing events and identifying dependencies among them event threading, an analogy to email threading that shows connections between related email messages .
2-16:We refer to the resulting interconnected structure of events as the event model of the topic .
2-17:Although this paper focuses on threading events within an existing news topic, we expect that such event based dependency structure more accurately reflects the structure of news than strictly bounded topics do .
2-18:From a user"s perspective, we believe that our view of a news topic as a set of interconnected events helps him her get a quick overview of the topic and also allows him her navigate through the topic faster .
2-19:The rest of the paper is organized as follows .
2-20:In section 2, we discuss related work .
2-21:In section 3, we define the problem and use an example to illustrate threading of events within a news topic .
2-22:In section 4, we describe how we built the corpus for our problem .
2-23:Section 5 presents our evaluation techniques while section 6 describes the techniques we use for modeling event structure .
2-24:In section 7 we present our experiments and results .
2-25:Section 8 concludes the paper with a few observations on our results and comments on future work .
2-26:446 .
3 RELATED WORK :
3-1:The process of threading events together is related to threading of electronic mail only by name for the most part .
3-2:Email usually incorporates a strong structure of referenced messages and consistently formatted subject headings though information retrieval techniques are useful when the structure breaks down [7] .
3-3:Email threading captures reference dependencies between messages and does not attempt to reflect any underlying real world structure of the matter under discussion .
3-4:Another area of research that looks at the structure within a topic is hierarchical text classification of topics [9, 6] .
3-5:The hierarchy within a topic does impose a structure on the topic, but we do not know of an effort to explore the extent to which that structure reflects the underlying event relationships .
3-6:Barzilay and Lee [5] proposed a content structure modeling technique where topics within text are learnt using unsupervised methods, and a linear order of these topics is modeled using hidden Markov models .
3-7:Our work differs from theirs in that we do not constrain the dependency to be linear .
3-8:Also their algorithms are tuned to work on specific genres of topics such as earthquakes, accidents, etc., while we expect our algorithms to generalize over any topic .
3-9:In TDT, researchers have traditionally considered topics as flatclusters [1] .
3-10:However, in TDT 2003, a hierarchical structure of topic detection has been proposed and [2] made useful attempts to adopt the new structure .
3-11:However this structure still did not explicitly model any dependencies between events .
3-12:In a work closest to ours, Makkonen [8] suggested modeling news topics in terms of its evolving events .
3-13:However, the paper stopped short of proposing any models to the problem .
3-14:Other related work that dealt with analysis within a news topic includes temporal summarization of news topics [4]. .
4 PROBLEM DEFINITION AND NOTATION :
4-1:In this work, we have adhered to the definition of event and topic as defined in TDT .
4-2:We present some definitions (in italics) and our interpretations (regular faced) below for clarity .
4-3:to users .
4-4:In TDT, a story is assumed to refer to only a single topic .
4-5:In this work, we also assume that each story discusses a single event .
4-6:In other words, a story is the smallest atomic unit in the hierarchy (topic event story) .
4-7:Clearly, both the assumptions are not necessarily true in reality, but we accept them for simplicity in modeling .
4-8:time and place [10] .
4-9:In our work, we represent an event by a set of stories that discuss it .
4-10:Following the assumption of atomicity of a story, this means that any set of distinct events can be represented by a set of non overlapping clusters of news stories .
4-11:event .
4-12:We expand on this definition and interpret a topic as a series of related events .
4-13:Thus a topic can be represented by clusters of stories each representing an event and a set of (directed or undirected) edges between pairs of these clusters representing the dependencies between these events .
4-14:We will describe this representation of a topic in more detail in the next section .
4-15:detects clusters of stories that discuss the same topic; Topic tracking detects stories that discuss a previously known topic [3] .
4-16:Thus TDT concerns itself mainly with clustering stories into topics that discuss them .
4-17:topic, and also captures the dependencies among the events .
4-18:Thus the main difference between event threading and TDT is that we focus our modeling effort on microscopic events rather than larger topics .
4-19:Additionally event threading models the relatedness or dependencies between pairs of events in a topic while TDT models topics as unrelated clusters of stories .
4-20:We first define our problem and representation of our model formally and then illustrate with the help of an example .
4-21:We are given a set of Ò news stories Ë ×½ ¡ ¡ ¡ ×Ò on a given topic Ì and their time of publication .
4-22:We define a set of events ½ ¡ ¡ ¡ Ñ with the following constraints: ¾ ¾ Ë (1) × Ø (2) × ¾ × Ø × ¾ (3) While the first constraint says that each event is an element in the power set of S, the second constraint ensures that each story can belong to at most one event .
4-23:The last constraint tells us that every story belongs to one of the events in .
4-24:In fact this allows us to define a mapping function from stories to events as follows: ´× µ iff × ¾ (4) Further, we also define a set of directed edges ´ µ which denote dependencies between events .
4-25:It is important to explain what we mean by this directional dependency: While the existence of an edge itself represents relatedness of two events, the direction could imply causality or temporal ordering .
4-26:By causal dependency we mean that the occurrence of event B is related to and is a consequence of the occurrence of event A .
4-27:By temporal ordering, we mean that event B happened after event A and is related to A but is not necessarily a consequence of A .
4-28:For example, consider the following two events: ‘plane crash" (event A) and ‘subsequent investigations" (event B) in a topic on a plane crash incident .
4-29:Clearly, the investigations are a result of the crash .
4-30:Hence an arrow from A to B falls under the category of causal dependency .
4-31:Now consider the pair of events ‘Pope arrives in Cuba"(event A) and ‘Pope meets Castro"(event B) in a topic that discusses Pope"s visit to Cuba .
4-32:Now events A and B are closely related through their association with the Pope and Cuba but event B is not necessarily a consequence of the occurrence of event A .
4-33:An arrow in such scenario captures what we call time ordering .
4-34:In this work, we do not make an attempt to distinguish between these two kinds of dependencies and our models treats them as identical .
4-35:A simpler (and hence less controversial) choice would be to ignore direction in the dependencies altogether and consider only undirected edges .
4-36:This choice definitely makes sense as a first step but we chose the former since we believe directional edges make more sense to the user as they provide a more illustrative flow chart perspective to the topic .
4-37:To make the idea of event threading more concrete, consider the example of TDT3 topic 30005, titled ‘Osama bin Laden"s Indictment" (in the 1998 news) .
4-38:This topic has 23 stories which form 5 events .
4-39:An event model of this topic can be represented as in figure indictment .
4-40:The occurrence of event 2, namely ‘Trial and Indictment of Osama" is dependent on the event of ‘evidence gathered by CIA", i.e., event 1 .
4-41:Similarly, event 2 influences the occurrences of events 3, 4 and 5, namely ‘Threats from Militants", ‘Reactions 447 from Muslim World" and ‘announcement of reward" .
4-42:Thus all the dependencies in the example are causal .
4-43:Extending our notation further, we call an event A a parent of B and B the child of A, if ´ µ ¾ .
4-44:We define an event model Å ´ µ to be a tuple of the set of events and set of dependencies .
