8 TECHNIQUES :
8-1:The task of event modeling can be split into two parts: clustering the stories into unique events in the topic and constructing dependencies among them .
8-2:In the following subsections, we describe techniques we developed for each of these sub tasks .
8-3:6.1 Clustering Each topic is composed of multiple events, so stories must be clustered into events before we can model the dependencies among them .
8-4:For simplicity, all stories in the same topic are assumed to be available at one time, rather than coming in a text stream .
8-5:This task is similar to traditional clustering but features other than word distributions may also be critical in our application .
8-6:In many text clustering systems, the similarity between two stories is the inner product of their tf idf vectors, hence we use it as one of our features .
8-7:Stories in the same event tend to follow temporal locality, so the time stamp of each story can be a useful feature .
8-8:Additionally, named entities such as person and location names are another obvious feature when forming events .
8-9:Stories in the same event tend to be related to the same person(s) and locations(s) .
8-10:In this subsection, we present an agglomerative clustering algorithm that combines all these features .
8-11:In our experiments, however, we study the effect of each feature on the performance separately using modified versions of this algorithm .
